\uc0\u8232 \cb3 If ongoing war is justified by predicating an extractivist mode of life upon the extinguishment of other modes of living, pesticides, in both their function and history, epitomize this double action of protection through extermination. The liquid movement of pesticides through private and public spaces highlights the arbitrariness and porousness of distinctions between wartime and peacetime and between domestic, agricultural, and militarized demarcations of territory. In the form of pesticide, freshly scented militarism coats crops, decorates walls, seeks out surfaces to cling to.\
\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 DDT \'97 WWII
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Developed in the 1940s by Monsanto and other agrochemical companies as one of the first modern synthetic insecticides, DDT (dichloro-diphenyl-trichloroethane) was initially and widely used to combat insect-borne human diseases in World War II. U.S. soldiers were issued DDT powder to sprinkle on their sleeping bags, allegedly with no adverse effects. DDT was hailed as another testament to the wonders of modern science, miraculously targeting only unwanted vermin with pinpoint precision, without causing any collateral damage.\
\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 DDT \'97 Wallpaper
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Even before the war had fully ended, the next one was being prepared. In 1944,\'a0
\f1\i Popular Mechanics\'a0
\f0\i0 magazine described \'93Our Next World War \'96 Against Insects\'94: \'93This one will be a long and bitter battle to crush the creeping, wriggling, flying, burrowing billions whose numbers and depredations baffle human comprehension.\'94 This prediction was verified when the U.S. War Production Board released DDT for civilian use in August 1945. This transition of markets marked less the end of one war than the transformed continuation of its mentality and deeper saturation (or rather, aeration) into everyday life:\'a0
\f1\i Time\'a0
\f0\i0 magazine announced DDT\'92s unrestricted release for civilian use on the same page that displayed photos of the atom bomb on Hiroshima.\
\cb1 \
\cb3 DDT was not only widely used on American farms, but within homes. With the full approval and reassurance of the government and a pointed advertorial targeting of \'93housewives,\'94 pesticides containing \'93the amazing wartime chemical DDT\'94 flew off suburban supermarket shelves. One such product was branded as Insect-O-Blitz, alluding to the Nazi military tactic. Another brand of aerosol spray, Bug a Boo, boasted in large, bold print that it contained DDT that far exceeded the US Government standards for insecticides. As one consumer, Sally Edelstein, remembered, the spray imparted a pine scent that felt \'93like bringing a bit of the outdoors right into our home.\'94\
\cb1 \
\cb3 This fragrance infused not just the living room and kitchen, but even the most highly guarded inner sanctum of the white suburban household and arguably the bastion of its moral panic and paranoia \'97 the nursery. In 1947, wallpaper company Trimz launched its line of DDT wallpapers for children\'92s rooms. Among other glowing commendations, one Trimz ad proclaimed:\cb1 \
